  "ancestors": [
    {
      "code": "pt-PT",
      "role": "superstrate",
      "weight": 0.45,
      "notes": "Portuguese superstrate: earliest Iberian lexifier; the Portuguese origin hypothesis (Goodman, Maurer) holds that Papiamentu originated from a Portuguese-based creole spoken by Sephardic Jews and Portuguese traders from the early 17th century."
    },
    {
      "code": "nl",
      "role": "superstrate",
      "weight": 0.35,
      "notes": "Dutch superstrate: Netherlands ruled Curaçao from 1634; Dutch colonial administration contributed vocabulary, and Dutch is still a co-official language. Official Curaçao orthography (2009) reflects phonemic principles distinct from Dutch etymology."
    }
  ],
  "notes": "Papiamentu (Curaçao/Bonaire) / Papiamento (Aruba). Iberian-based creole; official language of Curaçao, Aruba, and Bonaire. ~330,000 speakers. Two spelling conventions: Curaçao/Bonaire use phonemic orthography (papi-a-men-tu), Aruba uses etymological spelling closer to Spanish/Portuguese. KEY FEATURES: (1) FIVE-VOWEL SYSTEM: a/e/i/o/u; e and o vary [e]~[ɛ] and [o]~[ɔ]. (2) AFFRICATES: ch=[tʃ], dj=[dʒ]. (3) SIBILANTS: sh=[ʃ], zh=[ʒ], s=[s], z=[z]. (4) PALATAL NASAL: ñ=[ɲ] (from Spanish/Portuguese). (5) LL: renders [j] (from Spanish lateral, reanalysed as glide). (6) DIPHTHONGS: ai/ei/oi/au are phonemic. (7) STRESS: penultimate by default; stress-timed rhythm. One of the best-studied Atlantic creoles with the highest number of L1 speakers per capita in the Caribbean.",
